⠀
Guidelines:
⠀
**BLACK FEMMES TO THE FRONT**
⠀
1. Black people: You never need a reason to put your payment info. Don’t feel obligated to share more than just that!
⠀
2. You can also give! Black folks giving to each other is something we do anyway, feel free to do that here as well.
⠀
White and NBPOC:
⠀
1. Put a 💕 under the person you gave to, this is to spread the coin throughout the post and not to just the first 100 people who respond. If someone already has a 💕 doesn’t mean you can’t give to them! I will message you if you put a 💕 and don’t send $$, don’t try it.
⠀
2. Please share this post in your stories if you give and if you did not, someone you know will give!
⠀
3. Don’t tell folks you gave, it’s not about you.
⠀
4. Continue to agitate and demand the state give reparations to Black people.
⠀
*This is NOT reparations, reparations are owed from the state to Black people. Organizing for reparations is ongoing and I don’t want this post to diminish that specific ask.*

FATIMA JAMAL IS THE WRITER AND DIRECTOR of the film No Fats, No Femmes. Her practice considers those [of us] discarded (“the least of these”) and disappeared from Black collective imaginings and networks of care. Her art is where she pours out her feelings and assumes the work of getting her house in order—a “balm in Gilead.” She believes that we are better healed and whole than distracted and entertained.

She wonders where in the world Black trans women are truly safe.

node.text:
Elle Hearns (@soulfreedreams ) is an organizer, speaker, strategist, and writer. Elle’s voice as a strategist community organizer and speaker were formed from her upbringing in Columbus, Ohio as a youth organizer. Ms. Elle currently is the Executive Director of The Marsha P. Johnson (@mpjinstitute )Institute an organization founded in 2015 that works to create a crucial entry point for Black transgender women to advocate for an end to violence against all trans people through advocacy, transformative organizing, restoration, civil disobedience and direct action. The organization is credited for organizing the first ever National Day of Action for Black Trans Women in response to the murders of Amber Monroe, Kandis Capri, and Elisha Walker and held organized events in multiple cities including New York City, Chicago, and Washington DC.

Outside of their activism work Josh is passionate about creating art that represents rosier worlds where Black trans/queer people can live in happiness, peace and luxury.

Born and raised in South Central, Los Angeles, Vanessa Rochelle Lewis (@the.ugly.black.woman )(MFA) is a Queer, Fat, Black, Femme performer, facilitator, educator, writer, activist, healer, joyful weirdo, and Faerie Princess Mermaid Gangsta for The Revolution. Vanessa has danced across many professional and creative stages. She has been a Writer and Co-Managing Editor for acclaimed feminist magazines; a community college instructor at multiple Bay Area schools and radical transformative justice programs; a fundraiser and events coordinator for the Queer Women of Color Media Arts Project; the Artist In Residence for the Young Women Freedom Center where she facilitated Art Healing Workshops and a Master Class for formerly incarcerated women, trans, and non-binary people; and so much more. She is currently a core team member for Creating Freedom Movements (a year long social education project that supports grassroots visionary leaders to incubate healing and joy projects while learning more about the art, theory, and practice of social justice movements) and a Creative and Programming Consultant for the Positive Results Center (a family run organization founded by Lewis’s mother, Kandee Rochelle Lewis, to create awareness and prevent the trauma that comes from experiencing bullying, sexual abuse, dating, domestic or inter-personal violence and sex trafficking)
⠀
⠀
Vanessa Is the Founding Director of Reclaim UGLY: Uplift Glorify Love Yourself – And Create A World Where Others Can As Well! The Reclaim UGLY Healing Retreat and Transformative Imagination Conference in February 2022 - and so many transformative events between now and then (Like a free, online open mic and dream  and healing space for Black MaGes this Sat 2/27! Register here: bit.ly/reclaimUGLYopenmic). Stay updated at www.reclaimugly.org !!
⠀
Vanessa’s book Reclaim UGLY: Uplift Glorify Love Yourself And Create A World Where Others Can As Well will be published by North Atlantic Press and dispersed by Penguin Random House in October 2021 so stay tuned!!

Mia Wright-Ross (@mwrcollection) is a leathercraft’s artist and designer, who focuses her works in footwear & accessory design, sculpture, and lifestyle tools. She is the creative director and founder of MWR Collection, a luxury lifestyle artisan atelier based in New York City, and currently sold in Japan. She has also been a leading designer for a number of contemporary designer brands, including Calvin Klein, 3.1 Phillip Lim, Saks 5th Avenue, and Tibi. At Tibi, she was the Senior Footwear & Accessories Designer, where she oversaw all design & development in Italy & Brazil for 4 years. Presently, she is Adjunct Professor  at Parsons The New School of Design, a Freelance Footwear & Accessories Consultant for multiple brands,  and the 2020-21 Artist Fellow at The Museum of Art & Design. Her design client list includes J. Cole, CVSolange, Robert Glasper, Carmelo Anthony, Jimmy Butler, and work has been published in Footwear News, Harper’s Bazaar, Ebony Magazine, & Vogue.

Tracie Q. Gilbert, PhD (she/they) @thembianaiya is an educator, writer, researcher and consultant who uses conversation to help achieve sexual wellness and healing for Black people. Using a wide range of interactive, high-quality workshops and conversation series, Dr. Gilbert flips the script on “The Talk”, helping Black communities unpack the mental, historical, and cultural barriers that keep them from having honest, productive conversations about sex and sexuality.

Dr. Gilbert has nearly 25 years experience teaching urban youth, young adults, and their advocates. She received her Masters of Science in Education at the University of Pennsylvania, and her doctorate from the Center for Human Sexuality Studies at Widener University. Her dissertation on the lived experience of sexuality among African Americans won the CHSS 2019 Distinguished Dissertation Prize.

Dr. Gilbert has taught for a number of universities and non-profits, including Widener University, Christiana Healthcare Systems, Evoluer House, the Innovative Learning Institute, and the Center for Sex Education. She is the inaugural Minority Faculty Fellow at Murray State University, where she taught for 2 years in the departments of Psychology and Gender and Diversity Studies.

At present, Dr. Gilbert conducts direct services for youth and teen audiences through her independent agency, Thembi Anaiya, LLC.

C. Riley Snorton (he/they) @c.rileysnorton is a scholar, author, and activist whose work focuses on historical perspectives of gender and race, specifically Black transgender identities. node.text: One thing about me, I go hard for my siblings. Eb and I became college counselors over the past year just so the baby sister could fulfill her dream of leaving the isla and studying in the states. I won’t revisit the obstacles but just know there were MANY! But here she is, moving into college and ignoring all of my decor suggestions! You are going to shake shit up at Hampshire college cause you know these institutions are built on stolen land and made with Black peoples labor in mind not our humanity. Tear it down, sis! Love YOUUUUUUU @big._.fluff @_diegohart you are up next!! 💕💕💕

The skin routine no one asked for but wouldn’t hurt to have. 

In collaboration with @epi.logic and @bklynfaceandeye , I’m sharing how my skin has been on glow for the past several months. My hyperpigmentation has significantly reduced thanks to @epi.logic intentionally researched products. I have been doing this skin routine for the past three months and have not looked back.  I ran out of time in the reel, but don’t forget sunscreen!

node.text: Raise your hand if your anxiety has reached new heights lately! 👋🏾🙋🏾‍♀️ Had our first meeting with a midwife this week (more on this later) and they said, anxiety can also be caused by not regulating your blood sugar levels! 🤯🤯🤯🤯🤯 So waking up and not eating until 1pm is making me anxious!?? node.text: Martha’s Vineyard reminds me of New Orleans during Essence festival, Aunties getting their whole entire white toe season linen wearing lives! And sure there are some white people, but legit it seems they are outnumbered, praise the ancestors. This space has such rich Black and indigenous history, seeing Black people everywhere felt like being rubbed in Shea butter and jumping into some crisp white sheets. From celebrating @aunt_viv rotating around the sun another year, to the belly laughs at @t.moore212 Sag antics, to witnessing @jaythehandy incredible family, to the 4am convos about everything under the sun, to the 4 lobster rolls in four days-this trip was unforgettable. To go on vacation is a privilege, but to vacation amongst so many other Black folks where the only objective is seafood, beach, rest, repeat; felt like a dream. We will be back, Martha’s Vineyard and definitely for a longer stay. Another shout out to our incredible hosts, @aunt_viv and @jaythehandy y’all all we had to do was show up! Everything was handled! From the bottom of our harts, thank YOUUU!!

node.text:
Over the past two years and some change, I have been writing a book proposal. Most of my family and friends thought I was writing the book not knowing that for most people, there is an extensive process beforehand. The publishing world is no different than the rest of the world, anti Black, classists, colorist et al. I have been approached by publishing houses over the years but nothing ever came to fruition as I refused to be pigeon held in their imagination. My blood pressure has been raised more times than I care to admit at how quickly someone that has wealth, access to celebrity, pretty privilege, either is white or appeals to white people will get a book deal without having to write a book proposal.
⠀
As I sit on the other side of blank pages, late nights, never ending edits, meetings on meetings on meetings, frustration, tears, throwing drafts away, giving up and picking it up again, a new wave of emotions has greeted me. I am overwhelmed, grateful and in awe of what it took to get here. I want to say there are no words, but I know I better find them cause that’s what I’ll be doing for the next year lol.
⠀
I’m beyond thankful to the folks who held me down when on many occasions, I wanted to just stop. My family, friends and most notably Ebony, who has listened to every iteration of my imposter syndrome, put post it notes all around our first apt reminding me that it’s time for me to write a book and wore his lawyer cap to ensure we weren’t signing our lives away.
⠀
Special thanks to my book agent, @jen.marshall.3 for lighting some serious fire under me throughout this entire process. To my editor, @chelceeloraine at @randomhouse , all I wanted was a Black femme editor with a radical politic and there you were! I am through the roof excited (read: also terrified) to begin this opportunity of a lifetime.
⠀
Call me a ‘soon to be’ published author, if you nasty (screams)
#bookannouncement #imwritingabook 
⠀

“This is NOT a health care system” story:
Soooo out of nowhere my oncologist of five years was fired. I don’t know why and was only able to speculate with other patients through our frustration of never being informed this would be happening. I am now tasked with going with the new oncologist they have moved his patients to or to transfer to a new oncologist. Please note: they did NOT give me any background on the new oncologist either- just “there’s a new oncologist, want to schedule?”
⠀
I have been working on transferring as the assumption that I would stay at a doctors office that didn’t inform its patients the doctor they knew and trusted would be leaving doesn’t make me feel like they actually care about me. And I knew that, but the reminder that I’m just a $$ is always disorienting.
⠀
Transferring to a specialist is something I’ve never had to do and let me tell you, the few places I’ve talked to are acting like my transfer is stressful to THEM! I don’t think we talk enough about how bedside manner must begin before you see a doctor. I shouldn’t have to advocate for myself at all, but I certainly shouldn’t have to be demanding that folks not be rude to me if I don’t know the process to transfer medical records.
⠀
Let this be a reminder to not only check your chest but to be mindful of what folks are going through especially if you work in the health “care” system.
#feelitonthefirst #breastcancersurvivor #healthcare
